Starbucks Capstone Challenge¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains simulated data that mimics customer behavior on the Starbucks rewards mobile app. Once every few days, Starbucks sends out an offer to users of the mobile app. An offer can be merely an advertisement for a drink or an actual offer such as a discount or BOGO (buy one get one free). Some users might not receive any offer during certain weeks.

Not all users receive the same offer, and that is the challenge to solve with this data set.

Your task is to combine transaction, demographic and offer data to determine which demographic groups respond best to which offer type. This data set is a simplified version of the real Starbucks app because the underlying simulator only has one product whereas Starbucks actually sells dozens of products.

Every offer has a validity period before the offer expires. As an example, a BOGO offer might be valid for only 5 days. You'll see in the data set that informational offers have a validity period even though these ads are merely providing information about a product; for example, if an informational offer has 7 days of validity, you can assume the customer is feeling the influence of the offer for 7 days after receiving the advertisement.

You'll be given transactional data showing user purchases made on the app including the timestamp of purchase and the amount of money spent on a purchase. This transactional data also has a record for each offer that a user receives as well as a record for when a user actually views the offer. There are also records for when a user completes an offer.

Keep in mind as well that someone using the app might make a purchase through the app without having received an offer or seen an offer.

Example¶

To give an example, a user could receive a discount offer buy 10 dollars get 2 off on Monday. The offer is valid for 10 days from receipt. If the customer accumulates at least 10 dollars in purchases during the validity period, the customer completes the offer.

However, there are a few things to watch out for in this data set. Customers do not opt into the offers that they receive; in other words, a user can receive an offer, never actually view the offer, and still complete the offer. For example, a user might receive the "buy 10 dollars get 2 dollars off offer", but the user never opens the offer during the 10 day validity period. The customer spends 15 dollars during those ten days. There will be an offer completion record in the data set; however, the customer was not influenced by the offer because the customer never viewed the offer.

Cleaning¶

This makes data cleaning especially important and tricky.

You'll also want to take into account that some demographic groups will make purchases even if they don't receive an offer. From a business perspective, if a customer is going to make a 10 dollar purchase without an offer anyway, you wouldn't want to send a buy 10 dollars get 2 dollars off offer. You'll want to try to assess what a certain demographic group will buy when not receiving any offers.

Final Advice¶

Because this is a capstone project, you are free to analyze the data any way you see fit. For example, you could build a machine learning model that predicts how much someone will spend based on demographics and offer type. Or you could build a model that predicts whether or not someone will respond to an offer. Or, you don't need to build a machine learning model at all. You could develop a set of heuristics that determine what offer you should send to each customer (i.e., 75 percent of women customers who were 35 years old responded to offer A vs 40 percent from the same demographic to offer B, so send offer A).

Data Sets¶

The data is contained in three files:

  • portfolio.json - containing offer ids and meta data about each offer (duration, type, etc.)
  • profile.json - demographic data for each customer
  • transcript.json - records for transactions, offers received, offers viewed, and offers completed

Here is the schema and explanation of each variable in the files:

portfolio.json

  • id (string) - offer id
  • offer_type (string) - type of offer ie BOGO, discount, informational
  • difficulty (int) - minimum required spend to complete an offer
  • reward (int) - reward given for completing an offer
  • duration (int) - time for offer to be open, in days
  • channels (list of strings)

profile.json

  • age (int) - age of the customer
  • became_member_on (int) - date when customer created an app account
  • gender (str) - gender of the customer (note some entries contain 'O' for other rather than M or F)
  • id (str) - customer id
  • income (float) - customer's income

transcript.json

  • event (str) - record description (ie transaction, offer received, offer viewed, etc.)
  • person (str) - customer id
  • time (int) - time in hours since start of test. The data begins at time t=0
  • value - (dict of strings) - either an offer id or transaction amount depending on the record

Project Overview¶

This is Udacity Nanodegree Data Science capstone project - Starbucks Capstone Challenge: How to predict effective offers using user data from the Starbucks App. The data is simulated data that mimics customer behavior on the Starbucks rewards mobile app. Not all users receive the same offer, and that is the challenge to solve with this data sets.

Problem Statement¶

I will explore and try to understand more about Starbucks Customers different metrics based on customers personal information. Example is how they are distributed in different groups (gender, income and more). How the promotion offers affect Customer’s buying behavior. I will address main business questions below and will build machine learning algorithm to cluster how Starbucks should target the offers.

  • How the offer can be effective in the Starbucks app? Are those offers profitable?
  • How is the gender/income/average purchase /offer completion time and more distribution?
  • Can we predict with Machine Learning Algorithms how many clusters (users groups based on the behavior) should Starbucks use.

Metrics¶

Clustering is very well known techniques in Data Science. I choose to use Agglomerative Clustering. It is very common type of hierarchical clustering used to group objects in clusters based on their similarity. It uses a bottom-up approach, where each data point starts in its own cluster. These clusters are then joined, by taking the two most similar clusters together and merging them. Uses minimum variance method (ward) and this minimizes the total distance between clusters.

References used:

https://chrisalbon.com/machine_learning/clustering/agglomerative_clustering/

https://stackabuse.com/hierarchical-clustering-with-python-and-scikit-learn/

https://towardsdatascience.com/hierarchical-clustering-and-its-applications-41c1ad4441a6

def distplot_plt(what_to_plot, plttitle, pltxlabel, pltylabel, pltxlim=100):
    fig= plt.subplots(figsize=(6,4))
    sns.distplot(what_to_plot, kde = False, bins=10, color = 'blue',
                 hist_kws={'edgecolor':'black'})
    plt.xlim(0, pltxlim)
    plt.xlim(left=-0.2)
    plt.title(plttitle,size = 20)
    plt.xlabel(pltxlabel, size =15)
    plt.ylabel(pltylabel, size =15)
    plt.show()

# Define column drop func due to multiple reuse will be needed

def drop_columns(drop_columns,df,inplace=False):
    '''
    inputs:
    - drop_cols: list or string of column name to be dropped
    - df: dataframe from which column should be dropped
    - inplace: specify whether columns are dropped in place or not
    
    outputs:
    - Returns dataframe with dropped columns.
       
    '''
    df=df.drop(columns=drop_columns,axis=1,inplace=True)
    return df

def person_transactions_func(person):
    person_transactions = transcript[(transcript['person'] == person)
          & (transcript['key'] == 'amount')].reset_index()
    person_transactions['value'] = person_transactions['value'].copy().astype(float)
    person_transactions_mean = person_transactions.groupby('person').agg({'value':'mean'})
    
    return person_transactions , person_transactions_mean

# Get promotions per Customer, joins person and offer id

def offer_completed_person(person):
    offer_completed = pd.merge(
                        transcript_new[transcript_new['event'] == 'offer received']
                        , transcript_new[transcript_new['event'] == 'offer completed']
                        , left_on = ['person','value']
                        , right_on = ['person','value']
                        , how = 'left')

    completed_offer_person  = offer_completed[offer_completed['person'] == person]
    
    return completed_offer_person

def offer_completed_all():
    completed_offer_all = pd.merge(
                        transcript_new[transcript_new['event'] == 'offer received']
                        , transcript_new[transcript_new['event'] == 'offer completed']
                        , left_on = ['person','value']
                        , right_on = ['person','value']
                        , how = 'left')
    
    return completed_offer_all

# numpy 1.13 + needed to run successfully the code below

for person in np.unique(profile['id']):
    
    # Customer demographics pewr individual
    person_data = profile[profile['id'] == person][['id', 'gender', 'age', 'income', 'became_member_on']]
    
    # Transactions info
    person_transaction = total_transactions[total_transactions['person'] == person].reset_index()
    if len(person_transaction) > 0:
        person_transaction['last_purchase_in_days'] = person_transaction.time.diff()
        person_transaction.iloc[0, -1] = person_transactions.loc[0, 'time']
        person_aggregated_trs = person_transaction.groupby('person', as_index = False).agg(
        {
            'time': ['count']
            , 'value': ['mean', 'sum']
            , 'last_purchase_in_days': ['mean']  
        })
        # drop multy level colums
        person_aggregated_trs.columns = person_aggregated_trs.columns.droplevel(1)
        
        person_aggregated_trs.columns = ['person', 'total_transactions', 'avg_transaction_amount',
                                         'total_transactions_amount','avg_days_between_purchase'
                                        ]
    else:
        nan_array = [person, np.nan, np.nan, np.nan, np.nan]
        person_aggregated_trs = pd.DataFrame([nan_array]
                                         , columns = ['person', 'total_transactions', 'avg_transaction_amount',
                                                      'total_transactions_amount','avg_days_between_purchase'
                                                     ])
        
    personal_temp_df = pd.merge(person_data, person_aggregated_trs, how = 'inner', left_on = 'id', right_on = 'person')
    personal_temp_df.drop('id', axis = 1, inplace = True)
    
    
    for offer in ['discount','bogo']:
        globals()[offer + '_temp_df'] =  completed_offer_df[(completed_offer_df['person'] == person)
                       & (completed_offer_df['offer_type'] == offer)
                       ].groupby('person', as_index = False).agg({
                                                        'Completed_Offer':['count','sum']
                                                        , 'reward_value': ['mean']
                                                    })
        
        globals()[offer + '_temp_df'].columns = globals()[offer + '_temp_df'].columns.droplevel(1)
        globals()[offer + '_temp_df'].columns = [
                                        'person', offer + '_all_offers_received', offer + '_all_offers_completed',
                                        offer + '_average_reward']
        
        if len(globals()[offer + '_temp_df']) == 0:
            nan_array = [person,np.nan,np.nan,np.nan]
            globals()[offer + '_temp_df'] = globals()[offer + '_temp_df'].append(
                dict(zip(globals()[offer + '_temp_df'].columns, nan_array)), ignore_index=True)
    
    bogo_discounts_tmp = pd.merge(discount_temp_df, bogo_temp_df)
    bogo_discounts_tmp['informational_offers'] = len(completed_offer_df[(completed_offer_df['person'] == person)
                                                               & (completed_offer_df['offer_type'] == 'informational')])
    
    
    person_df_fin = pd.merge(personal_temp_df, bogo_discounts_tmp)
    
    customers_all_together = customers_all_together.append(person_df_fin)

Implementation¶

At this point DF 'customers_all_data' is ready for the next step clustering. All customer data is in one Data Frame so we can use for investigation how specific cluster(group of Customers responds to different offer or combinations of offers). Earlier I filled with 0 all NaN so I can use all of the features. I will apply k-means clustering to the dataset and use the average within-cluster distances from each point to their assigned cluster's centroid to decide on a number of clusters to keep.

There are technically 4 Customers clusters based on their behaviour(this is the reason I choose 4)

  • both offers - Bogo and Discount
  • prefer Bogo over Discount
  • prefer Discount over Bogo
  • none of the offers

# run k-means clustering on the data and...
# compute the average within-cluster distances.

def get_kmeans_score(data, center):
    '''
    returns the kmeans score regarding SSE for points to centers
    INPUT:
        data - the dataset you want to fit kmeans to
        center - the number of centers you want (the k value)
    OUTPUT:
        score - the SSE score for the kmeans model fit to the data
    '''
    #instantiate kmeans
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=center)

    # Then fit the model to your data using the fit method
    model = kmeans.fit(data)

    # Obtain a score related to the model fit
    score = np.abs(model.score(data))

    return score

scores = []
centers = list(range(1,11))

for center in centers:
    scores.append(get_kmeans_score(customers_all_data, center))
In [209]:

plt.plot(centers, scores, marker='o', color='b');
plt.xlabel('K');
plt.ylabel('SSE');
plt.title('SSE vs. K');

From the analisys of the above plot I do see a good visible elbow at 4 clusters. I choose to use Agglomerative Clustering (refference: https://chrisalbon.com/machine_learning/clustering/agglomerative_clustering/ https://stackabuse.com/hierarchical-clustering-with-python-and-scikit-learn/)

Conclusion¶

Starbucks Customers are ~ 60 % males , ~ 40% females . Most of all customers (60% + )are age between 45-60 years old. Average income is around 65K per year. Customers who didn't provide all of their personal information the trend is that they do not respond to offers.

After the analysis and using Machine Learning models offers can help Starbucks increasing the revenue but might not be really true for the profit. I also see a slow response rate. BOGO and discount shows better result than the Informational offers. Discount offers looks like a better choice first and if Customers do not respond BOGO should be the next step.

In Cluster_2 are most of the customers - 41.2%. Those are Customers will probably buy even without offer so might be not beneficial for Starbucks to sending to much offers to this group of people.

Discount offers has a higher response rate , and informational the lowest. Higher income people respond better to an offer and will more likely to spend more on Starbucks products.
